code:
We need to evaluate:

\begin{align*}
|(12-9i)(8+15i)| &= |12-9i| \times |8+15i|
\end{align*}

We calculate the absolute values (or modulus) of the two complex numbers separately.

First number: $12-9i$

The absolute value of a complex number $a+bi$ is $\sqrt{a²+b²}$.

So for the first number, we have:

\begin{align*}
|12-9i| = \sqrt{(12)² + (-9)²} = \sqrt{144 + 81} = \sqrt{225}
\end{align*}

$\sqrt{225} = 15$, so

\begin{align*}
|12-9i| = 15
\end{align*}

Second number: $8+15i$

Similarly, we have:

\begin{align*}
|8+15i| = \sqrt{(8)² + (15)²} = \sqrt{64 + 225} = \sqrt{289}
\end{align*}

$\sqrt{289} = 17$, so

\begin{align*}
|8+15i| = 17
\end{align*}

Now that we have both absolute values, we multiply them:

\begin{align*}
|(12-9i)(8+15i)| &= 15 \times 17 = 255
\end{align*}

The final result is 255.

Answer:
\boxed{255}

