The area of the parallelogram can be found by taking the magnitude of the cross product of the vectors $\bold{v}$ and $\bold{w}$.

However, since we're working with 2-dimensional vectors, we have to consider them as 3-dimensional vectors with a z-component of 0.

So let's write them as 3-dimensional vectors with a z-component of 0.

$\bold{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$

$\bold{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 11 \\ -2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$

Now we can find the cross product of these vectors.  The formula for the cross product of two vectors is

\begin{align*}
\bold{a} \times \bold{b} &= \det\begin{pmatrix}\bold{i} & \bold{j} & \bold{k}\\ a_1 & a_2 & a_3 \\ b_1 & b_2 & b_3 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (a_2b_3-a_3b_2)\bold{i} - (a_1b_3-a_3b_1)\bold{j} + (a_1b_2 - a_2b_1)\bold{k}
\end{align*}

Applying this to our vectors $\bold{v}$ and $\bold{w}$ gives:

\begin{align*}
\bold{v} \times \bold{w} &= \det\begin{pmatrix}\bold{i} & \bold{j} & \bold{k}\\5 &-3 & 0 \\11 & -2 & 0 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= ((-3)(0) - (0)(-2))\bold{i} - ((5)(0) - (0)(11))\bold{j} + ((5)(-2) - (-3)(11))\bold{k}\\
&= 0\bold{i} - 0\bold{j} +((-10) -(-33))\bold{k}\\
&= 23\bold{k}
\end{align*}

The magnitude of $\bold{v} \times \bold{w}$ is simply the absolute value of the coefficient of $\bold{k}$:

$\|\bold{v} \times \bold{w}\| = 23$

This is the area of the parallelogram.

question:
In the diagram below, triangle $ABC$ has been reflected over its median $\overline{AM}$ to produce triangle $AB'C'$.  If $AE = 6$, $EC =12$, and $BD = 10$, then find $AB$.

[asy]
size(250);
pair A,B,C,D,M,BB,CC,EE;
B = (0,0);
D = (10,0);
M = (15,0);
C=2*M;
A = D + (scale(1.2)*rotate(aCos((225-144-25)/120))*(M-D));
CC = D + D + D - A - A;
BB = reflect(A,M)*B;
EE = reflect(A,M)*D;
draw(M--A--BB--CC--A--B--C--A);
label("$M$",M,SE);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,SW);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$C'$",CC,S);
label("$B'$",BB,E);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",EE,N);
label("$12$",(EE+C)/2,N);
label("$6$",(A+EE)/2,S);
label("$10$",D/2,S);
[/asy]

